    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Afrocominella capensis&nbsp;</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_10438",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Fusiform medium-sized whelk with a constricted siphonal canal and a spire that is usually shorter than the aperture. Whorls gently rounded and with closely and uniformly-sized spiral ridges. Colour cream or grey to brownish orange, speckled and streaked with brown. Aperture white to purplish brown, operculum yellow-orange. Foot potentially entirely white. This is the Atlantic subspecies of <i>Africominella capensis.</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_10439",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": [
                {
                    "text": "",
                    "altText": "",
                    "title": "",
                    "imageUrl": {
                        "1x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-3233-250.webp",
                        "2x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-3233-500.webp",
                        "4x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-3233-1000.webp"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "text": "",
                    "altText": "",
                    "title": "",
                    "imageUrl": {
                        "1x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-3234-250.webp",
                        "2x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-3234-500.webp",
                        "4x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-3234-1000.webp"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "text": "",
                    "altText": "",
                    "title": "",
                    "imageUrl": {
                        "1x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-3235-250.webp",
                        "2x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-3235-500.webp",
                        "4x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-3235-1000.webp"
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Shell up to 50-60 mm.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_10440",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to the region, Namibia and South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Namibia to Cape Point.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_10441",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Fairly common and shells frequently found in beach drift. Living animals found under rocks and in crevices in low tide pools but more common subtidally.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_10442",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Whelks are predators, but the diet of this species is not specifically studied. Reported to feed on ‘small red worms’.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_10443",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Lays milky white, lens-shaped egg capsules that have a transparent window on top, which serves as an escape hatch for the young. Development unknown.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_10444",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Two subspecies are recognised and these are treated here as separate entries although officially considered a single species with unresolved taxonomy. <i>A. c. simoniana</i> has a higher, more elongated spire and occurs along the southern Cape coast to the eastern Transkei, with intermediate forms from False Bay to Cape Agulhas. <i>Afrocominella c. capensis </i>is plumper, with a lower spire, and is the Atlantic coast form.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_10445",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
